<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Dice_Distribution_(bar).svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"=
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Dice_Distribution=
_%28bar%29.svg/250px-Dice_Distribution_%28bar%29.svg.png" decoding=3D"async=
" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D=
"512" data-file-height=3D"384"></a><figcaption>The probabilities of rolling=
 several numbers using two dice</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Probability</b> is a branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a> and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a> con=
cerning <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Event_(probability_theory)=
" title=3D"Event (probability theory)">events</a> and numerical description=
s of how likely they are to occur.  The probability of an event is a number=
 between 0 and 1; the larger the probability, the more likely an event is t=
o occur.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>note 1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-Stuart_and_Ord_2009_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-Stuart_and_Ord_2009-2"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Feller_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-Feller-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This number is often =
expressed as a percentage (%), ranging from 0% to 100%. A simple example is=
 the tossing of a fair (unbiased) coin. Since the coin is fair, the two out=
comes ("heads" and "tails") are both equally probable; the probability of "=
heads" equals the probability of "tails"; and since no other outcomes are p=
ossible, the probability of either "heads" or "tails" is 1/2 (which could a=
lso be written as 0.5 or 50%).
</p><p>These concepts have been given an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Probability_axioms" title=3D"Probability axioms">axiomatic</a> mathe=
matical formalization in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probab=
ility_theory" title=3D"Probability theory">probability theory</a></i>, whic=
h is used widely in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Areas_of_study=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Areas of study">areas of study</a> such as=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">=
statistics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=
=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Science" title=3D"Science">science</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Finance" title=3D"Finance">finance</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Gambling" title=3D"Gambling">gambling</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title=3D"Artificial intellige=
nce">artificial intelligence</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Machine_learning" title=3D"Machine learning">machine learning</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer scien=
ce">computer science</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_the=
ory" title=3D"Game theory">game theory</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Philosophy" title=3D"Philosophy">philosophy</a> to, for examp=
le, draw inferences about the expected frequency of events. Probability the=
ory is also used to describe the underlying mechanics and regularities of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_systems" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Complex systems">complex systems</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite=
_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DProbability&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_probability#E=
tymology" title=3D"History of probability">History of probability =C2=A7&nb=
sp;Etymology</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossary_of_=
probability_and_statistics" title=3D"Glossary of probability and statistics=
">Glossary of probability and statistics</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likelihood" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Likelihood">Likelihood</a></div>
<p>The word <i>probability</i> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ety=
mology" title=3D"Etymology">derives</a> from the Latin <span title=3D"Latin=
-language text"><i lang=3D"la">probabilitas</i></span>, which can also mean=
 "<a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/probity" class=3D"extiw" title=
=3D"wiktionary:probity">probity</a>", a measure of the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Authority" title=3D"Authority">authority</a> of a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witness" title=3D"Witness">witness</a>=
 in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legal_case" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Legal case">legal case</a> in Europe, and often correlated w=
ith the witness's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobility" title=
=3D"Nobility">nobility</a>. In a sense, this differs much from the modern m=
eaning of <i>probability</i>, which in contrast is a measure of the weight =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical_evidence" title=3D"Em=
pirical evidence">empirical evidence</a>, and is arrived at from <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inductive_reasoning" title=3D"Inductive reas=
oning">inductive reasoning</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Statistical_inference" title=3D"Statistical inference">statistical inferen=
ce</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Emergence_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-Emergence-5"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Interpretations">Interpreta=
tions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DProbab=
ility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Interpretat=
ions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_interpre=
tations" title=3D"Probability interpretations">Probability interpretations<=
/a></div>
<p>When dealing with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experiment_(p=
robability_theory)" title=3D"Experiment (probability theory)">random experi=
ments</a> =E2=80=93 i.e., <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experime=
nt" title=3D"Experiment">experiments</a> that are <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Randomness" title=3D"Randomness">random</a> and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Well-defined_expression" title=3D"Well-define=
d expression">well-defined</a> =E2=80=93 in a purely theoretical setting (l=
ike tossing a coin), probabilities can be numerically described by the numb=
er of desired outcomes, divided by the total number of all outcomes.  This =
is referred to as <b>theoretical probability</b> (in contrast to <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical_probability" title=3D"Empirical pr=
obability">empirical probability</a>, dealing with probabilities in the con=
text of real experiments). The probability is a number between 0 and 1; the=
 larger the probability, the more likely the desired outcome is to occur. F=
or example, tossing a coin twice will yield "head-head", "head-tail", "tail=
-head", and "tail-tail" outcomes. The probability of getting an outcome of =
"head-head" is 1 out of 4 outcomes, or, in numerical terms, 1/4, 0.25 or 25=
%. The probability of getting an outcome of at least one head is 3 out of 4=
, or 0.75, and this event is more likely to occur. However, when it comes t=
o practical application, there are two major competing categories of probab=
ility interpretations, whose adherents hold different views about the funda=
mental nature of probability:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Objectivity_(philosophy)" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Objectivity (philosophy)">Objectivists</a> a=
ssign numbers to describe some objective or physical state of affairs. The =
most popular version of objective probability is <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Frequentist_probability" title=3D"Frequentist probability">f=
requentist probability</a>, which claims that the probability of a random e=
vent denotes the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequency_(sta=
tistics)" title=3D"Frequency (statistics)">relative frequency</a> of occurr=
ence</i> of an experiment's outcome when the experiment is repeated indefin=
itely. This interpretation considers probability to be the relative frequen=
cy "in the long run" of outcomes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-6"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> A modification of this is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prope=
nsity_probability" title=3D"Propensity probability">propensity probability<=
/a>, which interprets probability as the tendency of some experiment to yie=
ld a certain outcome, even if it is performed only once.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subjective_probability#Objecti=
ve_and_subjective_Bayesian_probabilities" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Su=
bjective probability">Subjectivists</a> assign numbers per subjective proba=
bility, that is, as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credence_(st=
atistics)" title=3D"Credence (statistics)">degree of belief</a>.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pr=
obability#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The degree of belief has been interpreted=
 as "the price at which you would buy or sell a bet that pays 1 unit of uti=
lity if E, 0 if not E",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> altho=
ugh that interpretation is not universally agreed upon.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability=
#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> The most popular version of subjective probability=
 is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_probability" title=3D=
"Bayesian probability">Bayesian probability</a>, which includes expert know=
ledge as well as experimental data to produce probabilities. The expert kno=
wledge is represented by some (subjective) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Prior_probability_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pri=
or probability distribution">prior probability distribution</a>. These data=
 are incorporated in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likelihood_=
function" title=3D"Likelihood function">likelihood function</a>. The produc=
t of the prior and the likelihood, when normalized, results in a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_probability_distribution" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Posterior probability distribution">posterior probab=
ility distribution</a> that incorporates all the information known to date.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Aumann%27s_agreement_theorem" title=3D"Aumann's agreement t=
heorem">Aumann's agreement theorem</a>, Bayesian agents whose prior beliefs=
 are similar will end up with similar posterior beliefs. However, sufficien=
tly different priors can lead to different conclusions, regardless of how m=
uch information the agents share.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-11"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DProbability&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_probabili=
ty" title=3D"History of probability">History of probability</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_st=
atistics" title=3D"History of statistics">History of statistics</a></div>
<p>The scientific study of probability is a modern development of mathemati=
cs. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gambling" title=3D"Gambling">G=
ambling</a> shows that there has been an interest in quantifying the ideas =
of probability throughout history, but exact mathematical descriptions aros=
e much later. There are reasons for the slow development of the mathematics=
 of probability. Whereas games of chance provided the impetus for the mathe=
matical study of probability, fundamental issues <sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite=
_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 2<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> are still obscured by superstitions.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro=
bability#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Jeffre=
y" title=3D"Richard Jeffrey">Richard Jeffrey</a>, "Before the middle of the=
 seventeenth century, the term 'probable' (Latin <i>probabilis</i>) meant <=
i>approvable</i>, and was applied in that sense, univocally, to opinion and=
 to action. A probable action or opinion was one such as sensible people wo=
uld undertake or hold, in the circumstances."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jeffrey_14=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilit=
y#cite_note-Jeffrey-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, in legal contexts especially,=
 'probable' could also apply to propositions for which there was good evide=
nce.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Franklin_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-Franklin-15"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
