=3D"1682" data-file-height=3D"2204"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Christiaan_Huygens" title=3D"Christiaan Huygens">Christia=
an Huygens</a> published one of the first books on probability (17th centur=
y).</figcaption></figure>
<p>The sixteenth-century <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italians"=
 title=3D"Italians">Italian</a> polymath <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Gerolamo_Cardano" title=3D"Gerolamo Cardano">Gerolamo Cardano</a> de=
monstrated the efficacy of defining <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Odds" title=3D"Odds">odds</a> as the ratio of favourable to unfavourable =
outcomes (which implies that the probability of an event is given by the ra=
tio of favourable outcomes to the total number of possible outcomes<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Probability#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>).
Aside from the elementary work by Cardano, the doctrine of probabilities da=
tes to the correspondence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierr=
e_de_Fermat" title=3D"Pierre de Fermat">Pierre de Fermat</a> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaise_Pascal" title=3D"Blaise Pascal">Blais=
e Pascal</a> (1654). <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christiaan_Hu=
ygens" title=3D"Christiaan Huygens">Christiaan Huygens</a> (1657) gave the =
earliest known scientific treatment of the subject.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#ci=
te_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jakob_Bern=
oulli" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Jakob Bernoulli">Jakob Bernoulli</a>'=
s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ars_Conjectandi" title=3D"Ars=
 Conjectandi">Ars Conjectandi</a></i> (posthumous, 1713) and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_de_Moivre" title=3D"Abraham de Moivre">A=
braham de Moivre</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Doct=
rine_of_Chances" title=3D"The Doctrine of Chances">Doctrine of Chances</a><=
/i> (1718) treated the subject as a branch of mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabi=
lity#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Ian_Hacking" title=3D"Ian Hacking">Ian Hacking</a>'s <i>The Emergence of P=
robability</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Emergence_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-Emergence-5"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Franklin_(philosop=
her)" title=3D"James Franklin (philosopher)">James Franklin's</a> <i>The Sc=
ience of Conjecture</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> for=
 histories of the early development of the very concept of mathematical pro=
bability.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theory_of_errors" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Theory of errors">theory of errors</a> may be tra=
ced back to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Cotes" title=3D"=
Roger Cotes">Roger Cotes</a>'s <i>Opera Miscellanea</i> (posthumous, 1722),=
 but a memoir prepared by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_S=
impson" title=3D"Thomas Simpson">Thomas Simpson</a> in 1755 (printed 1756) =
first applied the theory to the discussion of errors of observation.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Probability#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The reprint (1757) of this memoir =
lays down the axioms that positive and negative errors are equally probable=
, and that certain assignable limits define the range of all errors. Simpso=
n also discusses continuous errors and describes a probability curve.
</p><p>The first two laws of error that were proposed both originated with =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre-Simon_Laplace" title=3D"Pie=
rre-Simon Laplace">Pierre-Simon Laplace</a>. The first law was published in=
 1774, and stated that the frequency of an error could be expressed as an e=
xponential function of the numerical magnitude of the error&nbsp;=E2=80=93 =
disregarding sign. The second law of error was proposed in 1778 by Laplace,=
 and stated that the frequency of the error is an exponential function of t=
he square of the error.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wilson1923_21-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-Wilson1=
923-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> The second law of error is called the normal distributi=
on or the Gauss law. "It is difficult historically to attribute that law to=
 Gauss, who in spite of his well-known precocity had probably not made this=
 discovery before he was two years old."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wilson1923_21-1=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#=
cite_note-Wilson1923-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Bernoulli" title=3D"=
Daniel Bernoulli">Daniel Bernoulli</a> (1778) introduced the principle of t=
he maximum product of the probabilities of a system of concurrent errors.
</p>
