</p><p>In the nineteenth century, authors on the general theory included <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Laplace">Laplace</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sylvestr=
e_Lacroix" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sylvestre Lacroix">Sylvestre Lacr=
oix</a> (1816), Littrow (1833), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ad=
olphe_Quetelet" title=3D"Adolphe Quetelet">Adolphe Quetelet</a> (1853), <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Dedekind" title=3D"Richard De=
dekind">Richard Dedekind</a> (1860), Helmert (1872), <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Laurent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hermann =
Laurent">Hermann Laurent</a> (1873), Liagre, Didion and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Pearson" title=3D"Karl Pearson">Karl Pearson</a>=
. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustus_De_Morgan" title=3D"Aug=
ustus De Morgan">Augustus De Morgan</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/George_Boole" title=3D"George Boole">George Boole</a> improved th=
e exposition of the theory.
</p><p>In 1906, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrey_Markov" tit=
le=3D"Andrey Markov">Andrey Markov</a> introduced<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite=
_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> the notion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Markov_chains" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Markov chains">Markov chain=
s</a>, which played an important role in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Stochastic_process" title=3D"Stochastic process">stochastic processe=
s</a> theory and its applications. The modern theory of probability based o=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_(mathematics)" title=3D"=
Measure (mathematics)">measure theory</a> was developed by <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrey_Kolmogorov" title=3D"Andrey Kolmogorov">And=
rey Kolmogorov</a> in 1931.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-24"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On the geometric side, contributors to <i>The Educational Times</i> =
included Miller, Crofton, McColl, Wolstenholme, Watson, and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artemas_Martin" title=3D"Artemas Martin">Artemas =
Martin</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> See <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral_geometry" title=3D"Integral geometry"=
>integral geometry</a> for more information.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Theory">Theory</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DProbability&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Theory"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" =
title=3D"Probability theory">Probability theory</a></div>
<p>Like other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theory" title=3D"The=
ory">theories</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability=
_theory" title=3D"Probability theory">theory of probability</a> is a repres=
entation of its concepts in formal terms&nbsp;=E2=80=93 that is, in terms t=
hat can be considered separately from their meaning. These formal terms are=
 manipulated by the rules of mathematics and logic, and any results are int=
erpreted or translated back into the problem domain.
</p><p>There have been at least two successful attempts to formalize probab=
ility, namely the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kolmogorov" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kolmogorov">Kolmogorov</a> formulation and the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Threlkeld_Cox" title=3D"Ric=
hard Threlkeld Cox">Cox</a> formulation. In Kolmogorov's formulation (see a=
lso <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_space" title=3D"Pr=
obability space">probability space</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Set_(mathematics)" title=3D"Set (mathematics)">sets</a> are interpre=
ted as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Event_(probability_theory)"=
 title=3D"Event (probability theory)">events</a> and probability as a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_(mathematics)" title=3D"Measure=
 (mathematics)">measure</a> on a class of sets. In <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Cox%27s_theorem" title=3D"Cox's theorem">Cox's theorem</a>=
, probability is taken as a primitive (i.e., not further analyzed), and the=
 emphasis is on constructing a consistent assignment of probability values =
to propositions. In both cases, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Probability_axioms" title=3D"Probability axioms">laws of probability</a> =
are the same, except for technical details.
</p><p>There are other methods for quantifying uncertainty, such as the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dempster%E2%80%93Shafer_theory" title=
=3D"Dempster=E2=80=93Shafer theory">Dempster=E2=80=93Shafer theory</a> or <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Possibility_theory" title=3D"Possib=
ility theory">possibility theory</a>, but those are essentially different a=
nd not compatible with the usually-understood laws of probability.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DProbability&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Applications"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>Probability theory is applied in everyday life in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Risk" title=3D"Risk">risk</a> assessment and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_model" title=3D"Statistical model=
">modeling</a>. The insurance industry and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Market_(economics)" title=3D"Market (economics)">markets</a> use <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Actuarial_science" title=3D"Actuari=
al science">actuarial science</a> to determine pricing and make trading dec=
isions. Governments apply probabilistic methods in <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Environmental_regulation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"E=
nvironmental regulation">environmental regulation</a>, entitlement analysis=
, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_regulation" title=
=3D"Financial regulation">financial regulation</a>.
</p><p>An example of the use of probability theory in equity trading is the=
 effect of the perceived probability of any widespread Middle East conflict=
 on oil prices, which have ripple effects in the economy as a whole. An ass=
essment by a commodity trader that a war is more likely can send that commo=
dity's prices up or down, and signals other traders of that opinion. Accord=
ingly, the probabilities are neither assessed independently nor necessarily=
 rationally. The theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Behavio=
ral_finance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Behavioral finance">behavioral =
finance</a> emerged to describe the effect of such <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Groupthink" title=3D"Groupthink">groupthink</a> on pricing=
, on policy, and on peace and conflict.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-26">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>In addition to financial assessment, probability can be used to anal=
yze trends in biology (e.g., disease spread) as well as ecology (e.g., biol=
ogical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punnett_squares" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Punnett squares">Punnett squares</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Edwards_2012_2_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-Edwards_2012_2-27"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As with fin=
ance, risk assessment can be used as a statistical tool to calculate the li=
kelihood of undesirable events occurring, and can assist with implementing =
protocols to avoid encountering such circumstances. Probability is used to =
design <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Games_of_chance" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Games of chance">games of chance</a> so that casinos c=
an make a guaranteed profit, yet provide payouts to players that are freque=
nt enough to encourage continued play.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-28"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>Another significant application of probability theory in everyday li=
fe is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reliability_(statistics)" ti=
tle=3D"Reliability (statistics)">reliability</a>. Many consumer products, s=
uch as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automobiles" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Automobiles">automobiles</a> and consumer electronics, use=
 reliability theory in product design to reduce the probability of failure.=
 Failure probability may influence a manufacturer's decisions on a product'=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warranty" title=3D"Warranty">war=
ranty</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cache_language_model" t=
itle=3D"Cache language model">cache language model</a> and other <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_Language_Model" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Statistical Language Model">statistical language models</a> =
that are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_language_=
processing" title=3D"Natural language processing">natural language processi=
ng</a> are also examples of applications of probability theory.
</p>
