<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relation_to_randomness_and_=
probability_in_quantum_mechanics">Relation to randomness and probability in=
 quantum mechanics</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?t=
itle=3DProbability&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Relation to randomness and probability in quantum mechanics"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomness" title=3D=
"Randomness">Randomness</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_fluctuation#Inte=
rpretations" title=3D"Quantum fluctuation">Quantum fluctuation =C2=A7&nbsp;=
Interpretations</a></div>
<p>In a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinism" title=3D"Dete=
rminism">deterministic</a> universe, based on <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Newtonian_mechanics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Newtonian m=
echanics">Newtonian</a> concepts, there would be no probability if all cond=
itions were known (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace%27s_dem=
on" title=3D"Laplace's demon">Laplace's demon</a>) (but there are situation=
s in which <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chaos_theory" title=3D"=
Chaos theory">sensitivity to initial conditions</a> exceeds our ability to =
measure them, i.e. know them).  In the case of a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Roulette" title=3D"Roulette">roulette</a> wheel, if the forc=
e of the hand and the period of that force are known, the number on which t=
he ball will stop would be a certainty (though as a practical matter, this =
would likely be true only of a roulette wheel that had not been exactly lev=
elled =E2=80=93 as Thomas A. Bass' <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Eudaemons" title=3D"Eudaemons">Newtonian Casino</a> revealed).  This also =
assumes knowledge of inertia and friction of the wheel, weight, smoothness,=
 and roundness of the ball, variations in hand speed during the turning, an=
d so forth. A probabilistic description can thus be more useful than Newton=
ian mechanics for analyzing the pattern of outcomes of repeated rolls of a =
roulette wheel. Physicists face the same situation in the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinetic_theory_of_gases" title=3D"Kinetic theory of=
 gases">kinetic theory of gases</a>, where the system, while deterministic =
<i>in principle</i>, is so complex (with the number of molecules typically =
the order of magnitude of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avog=
adro_constant" title=3D"Avogadro constant">Avogadro constant</a> <span clas=
s=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7023602000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>=
6.02<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10=
<sup>23</sup></span>) that only a statistical description of its properties=
 is feasible.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=
=3D"Probability theory">Probability theory</a> is required to describe quan=
tum phenomena.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A revolutiona=
ry discovery of early 20th century <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a> was the random character of all phy=
sical processes that occur at sub-atomic scales and are governed by the law=
s of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"Q=
uantum mechanics">quantum mechanics</a>. The objective <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wave_function" title=3D"Wave function">wave function</=
a> evolves deterministically but, according to the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Copenhagen_interpretation" title=3D"Copenhagen interpretat=
ion">Copenhagen interpretation</a>, it deals with probabilities of observin=
g, the outcome being explained by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Wave_function_collapse" title=3D"Wave function collapse">wave function co=
llapse</a> when an observation is made. However, the loss of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinism" title=3D"Determinism">determinism</=
a> for the sake of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Instrumentalism=
" title=3D"Instrumentalism">instrumentalism</a> did not meet with universal=
 approval. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein" title=
=3D"Albert Einstein">Albert Einstein</a> famously <a href=3D"https://de.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein#Quellenangaben_und_Anmerkungen" class=3D"ex=
tiw" title=3D"de:Albert Einstein">remarked</a> in a letter to <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max_Born" title=3D"Max Born">Max Born</a>: "I a=
m convinced that God does not play dice".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-39=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> Like Einstein, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erwin=
_Schr%C3%B6dinger" title=3D"Erwin Schr=C3=B6dinger">Erwin Schr=C3=B6dinger<=
/a>, who <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schr%C3%B6dinger_equation=
#Historical_background_and_development" title=3D"Schr=C3=B6dinger equation"=
>discovered</a> the wave function, believed quantum mechanics is a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Statistical">statistical</a> approximation of an underlying determinist=
ic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reality" title=3D"Reality">real=
ity</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Probability#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In some modern inte=
rpretations of the statistical mechanics of measurement, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_decoherence" title=3D"Quantum decoherence">q=
uantum decoherence</a> is invoked to account for the appearance of subjecti=
vely probabilistic experimental outcomes.
</p>
