le=3D"Jump up">^</a></b></span> <span class=3D"reference-text">Strictly spe=
aking, a probability of 0 indicates that an event <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Almost_surely" title=3D"Almost surely"><i>almost</i> never<=
/a> takes place, whereas a probability of 1 indicates than an event <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almost_surely" title=3D"Almost surely"><i=
>almost</i> certainly</a> takes place. This is an important distinction whe=
n the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_space" title=3D"Sampl=
e space">sample space</a> is infinite. For example, for the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_uniform_distribution" title=3D"Continu=
ous uniform distribution">continuous uniform distribution</a> on the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real<=
/a> interval [5, 10], there are an infinite number of possible outcomes, an=
d the probability of any given outcome being observed =E2=80=93 for instanc=
e, exactly 7 =E2=80=93 is 0. This means that an observation will <i>almost =
surely not</i> be exactly 7. However, it does <b>not</b> mean that exactly =
7 is <i>impossible</i>. Ultimately some specific outcome (with probability =
0) will be observed, and one possibility for that specific outcome is exact=
ly 7.</span>
</li>
